Clearly, for PNG women who prioritize morality, abortion is a minority issue.

There is no place for any institutionalized feminisms in such a culture. We need to learn to live within the women’s particular culture collectives, respecting the diversity and fluidity inherent in every PNG culture and truly embracing women in all our complex and complicated glory.

This judgment also leads us to question not only the confines of institutionalized feminisms but also its claim to the moral high ground as PNG women in all our diversity the start of this enquiry into Poststructuralist philosophy.

As a moral issue, the problem with feminism is its privileging of what we ‘should’ do over what is and has always been. Such posturing is mired in ignorance, factual distortion and the complete disregard of Papua New Guinean women’s own forms of female resistance throughout history; forms which have proven both historically and contemporaneously effective - methods which require no legal interventions.

Feminism eschews these far more realistic means to make any headway in PNG’s socio-cultural landscape while at the same time it pretends to champion the rights of women through legal interventions and focus solely on wanting to see ourselves somehow contained in legal apparatuses.
